The paper deals with the intersection of Geometry and Complexity Theory, specifically the problem of derandomizing Noether's Normalization Lemma (NNL) for explicit varieties. This suggests that the paper could belong to cs.AG (Algebraic Geometry) or cs.CC (Computational Complexity). The paper also mentions the complexity classes EXPSPACE and P, indicating a focus on computational complexity, which further supports cs.CC as a likely category. The use of multilinear polynomials and arithmetic circuits suggests a connection to cs.SC (Symbolic Computation), while the mention of the black-box derandomization hypothesis (BDH) for polynomial identity testing (PIT) suggests a connection to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science). Overall, cs.CC and cs.AG seem to be the most likely categories, followed by cs.DS, cs.LO, and cs.SC.
